  "texts": [
    "The statement of the proposition in the case J ∂ > I ∂ is then the following: If we express a in the basis a ′′, b ′′, c ′′ and in the basis a, b ′, c ′′, then the coefficient of c ′′ is the same in both expressions.",
    "Let us also explain the case I ∂ > J ∂: Let us assume that, if we express a in terms of a, b, c, the coefficient of a is 1 (this can always be achieved simply by rescaling one of these bases).",
    "The statement of the second proposition then says the following in this case: Express a in terms of the basis a, b ′, c ′′, and express a in terms of the basis a ′′, b ′′, c ′′, then the coefficients of c ′′ in both expressions only differ by a sign.",
    "Both statements can be checked by an easy computation, and it is tedious but not difficult to generalise these arguments to more complicated cases, as we indicated in the above proof above.",
    "Let us note that, if I ∂ ̸ = J ∂, then the deformation datum in the above proposition does not change if we replace the splitting coming from (I ∂) -by the one from (I ∂) +, and similarly for the splitting on J ∂."
